---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
const updated = 'June 14, 2026';
---

<Base title="Privacy Policy — lirova">
  <section class="detail wrap">
    <a href="/" class="back">&larr; Back home</a>
    <div class="prose">
      <h1>Privacy Policy</h1>
      <p class="meta-line">Last updated: {updated}</p>

      <p>
        This policy explains how <strong>lirova</strong> (&ldquo;we,&rdquo; &ldquo;us&rdquo;)
        handles information across two things: this website
        (<code>lirova.github.io</code>) and the self-hosted lirova applications you
        may run (including any application that connects to your Google account).
        The short version: <strong>we collect as little as possible, and for the
        self-hosted apps we never receive a copy of your data at all.</strong>
      </p>

      <h2>1. The website</h2>
      <p>
        This site is a static page. It sets <strong>no cookies</strong>, runs
        <strong>no analytics</strong>, and uses <strong>no third-party trackers or
        advertising</strong>.
      </p>
      <p>
        If you use the contact form, you send us your <strong>name, email, optional
        company, and your message</strong>. That information is delivered to a
        private inbox we control and is used for one purpose: to reply to you. It is
        not sold, rented, or shared with anyone, and we keep it only as long as
        needed to handle your enquiry.
      </p>

      <h2>2. The self-hosted applications</h2>
      <p>
        Our applications are <strong>self-hosted</strong>: they run on
        <em>your</em> machines, in <em>your</em> environment, using <em>your</em>
        own credentials and API keys. Because of this architecture:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>We do not receive, store, or transmit your data.</strong> Your
          content stays on infrastructure you control.</li>
        <li>If an application connects to your Google account (for example, to read
          Gmail or Calendar), it requests access <em>on your device</em> and uses
          that access <em>locally</em> to provide the feature you asked for.</li>
        <li>OAuth tokens and any cached data are stored <strong>locally on your own
          machine</strong>, encrypted at rest (AES-256-GCM), never on our servers.</li>
        <li>We never use your Google data for advertising, never sell it, and never
          transfer it to third parties.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>3. Google API Services — Limited Use</h2>
      <p>
        lirova&rsquo;s use and transfer of information received from Google APIs to
        any other app will adhere to the
        <a href="https://developers.google.com/terms/api-services-user-data-policy"
           target="_blank" rel="noopener">Google API Services User Data Policy</a>,
        including the <strong>Limited Use</strong> requirements. Specifically, data
        obtained through Google APIs is used only to provide or improve the
        user-facing features you have enabled, is processed locally in your own
        environment, is not transferred to others except as necessary to provide
        those features, and is not used for advertising or sold to anyone.
      </p>

      <h2>4. Data sharing</h2>
      <p>
        We do not share your personal information with third parties. The
        self-hosted model means there is no central copy of your data for anyone to
        access, leak, or sell.
      </p>

      <h2>5. Security</h2>
      <p>
        Website enquiries are delivered over encrypted (HTTPS) connections to a
        private inbox. In the self-hosted applications, sensitive data is encrypted
        at rest on your own device. No system is perfectly secure, but because your
        data does not leave your environment, the exposure surface is minimal by
        design.
      </p>

      <h2>6. Your rights</h2>
      <p>
        You can ask us to access or delete any information you sent us via the
        contact form. For the self-hosted applications, you are in full control of
        your own data and can delete it directly. To make a request, email
        <span class="cta-email" data-b="bGlyb3ZhQHByb3Rvbi5tZQ=="></span>.
      </p>

      <h2>7. Children</h2>
      <p>
        Our services are intended for businesses and professionals and are not
        directed to children under 16. We do not knowingly collect their data.
      </p>

      <h2>8. Changes</h2>
      <p>
        We may update this policy as the services evolve. Material changes will be
        reflected by the &ldquo;last updated&rdquo; date above.
      </p>

      <h2>9. Contact</h2>
      <p>
        Questions about this policy? Email
        <span class="cta-email" data-b="bGlyb3ZhQHByb3Rvbi5tZQ=="></span>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <script>
    // Assemble the contact address at runtime so it isn't sitting in the page
    // source for scrapers (same anti-scrape stance as the contact form).
    document.querySelectorAll<HTMLElement>('.cta-email').forEach((el) => {
      const addr = atob(el.dataset.b || '');
      const a = document.createElement('a');
      a.href = `mailto:${addr}`;
      a.textContent = addr;
      el.replaceWith(a);
    });
  </script>
</Base>
